Plotting in base R (part 1 of 2)

Jordan S Read, Steve Corsi

follow along or view later:

  • github.usgs-r.io/plotting_01.html

Goals for Part I of R plotting

  • scatter plots: plotting x vs y data with axis labels
  • boxplots: plotting simple distribution of one or more variables
  • barcharts: histograms and stacked bar charts
  • customization: symbols, colors, legends, multiple y- or x-axes, and graphics layout
  • exporting figures: saving figures to a local file

Why R?

  • Performace: stable, light and fast
  • Support network
    • documentation, community, developers
  • Reproducibility
    • anyone anywhere can reproduce results
    • enables dissemination - this presentation is a .Rmd file!
  • Versatility: unified solution to almost any numerical problem, graphical capabilities
  • Testing: integrated “R package” testing limits bugs

Parse data into something we can use

dates <- as.POSIXct(site_data$dateTime,tz =  site_data$tz_cd)
observe <- as.numeric(site_data[, ncol(site_data)])
nwis_df <- data.frame('DateTime' = dates,
                      'variable' = observe)

plot a timeseries

Code in R:
plot(nwis_df, 
     ylab = 'Dissolved oxygen (mg/L)', 
     xlab = "")

Explanation
  • plot timeseries data for parameter
  • specify y-axis label (to parameter name)
  • remove x-axis label

plot a timeseries

Code in R:
plot(nwis_df, 
     ylab = 'Dissolved oxygen (mg/L)', 
     xlab = "")
abline(h = 4)
below_thresh = nwis_df[, 2] < 4
points(nwis_df[below_thresh, ], col = 'red')

Explanation
  • plot timeseries data for parameter
  • specify y-axis label (to parameter name)
  • remove x-axis label
  • add a threshold line
  • highlight points below threshold

create a boxplot

Code in R:
month <- months(nwis_df$DateTime)
June_data <- head(nwis_df[month == 'June', 2], 2000)
Sept_data <- head(nwis_df[month == 'September', 2], 2000)

boxplot(x = data.frame(Sept_data, June_data), 
        ylab = 'Dissolved oxygen (mg/L)')

Explanation
  • subset the data by June and September
  • use the first 2000 observations for each
  • create a box plot for the two months

create a histogram

Code in R:
hist(nwis_df[, 2], freq = FALSE, xlab = 'Dissolved oxygen (mg/L)')

Explanation
  • create a simple histogram of nwis_df

create a histogram

Code in R:
p1 <- hist(June_data, plot = FALSE)
p2 <- hist(Sept_data, plot = FALSE)
colr1 <- rgb(0,0,1,1/4)
colr2 <- rgb(1,0,0,1/4)
plot(p1, col=colr1, main='Dissolved oxygen',freq=F,xlab="")
plot(p2, col=colr2, xlim=c(0,10),add=T,new=F,freq=F)
legend("topright", legend = c('June','Sept'), 
       fill = c(colr1, colr2))

Explanation
  • create a two variable histogram of nwis_df

saving/exporting a figure

Code in R:
png(filename = 'test_fig.png', width = 700)
plot(p1, col=colr1, main='Dissolved oxygen',freq=F,xlab="")
plot(p2, col=colr2, xlim=c(0,10),add=T,new=F,freq=F)
legend("topright", legend = c('June','Sept'), 
       fill = c(colr1, colr2),cex = 2)
dev.off()
